Description: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear is convex and shows organic impressions like from a leather bag, in the break one impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.12 cm. The front has a small flat area with downwards bent sides with finger impressions. On the flat area the lower half of an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a thin circumferential line. In the middle on the left an unidentified sign, to the right of it a seated baboon, facing towards the left, the head is not preserved. Underneath a very thin n line on top of a straight line, then a very thin mr-sign and a nb-sign at the lower end.
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
